<subSubSection lastPageId="49" lastPageNumber="50" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,1681,2030]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1753,1778]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Description</emphasis>
. 
<typeStatus box="[357,461,1753,1778]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Holotype</typeStatus>
(
<collectionCode box="[483,566,1753,1777]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">USNM</collectionCode>
19340) damaged, broken in two portions, partly dehydrated, body dark, slightly fusiform (
<figureCitation box="[365,476,1789,1814]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1613,1635]" captionTargetBox="[175,1416,673,1567]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[171,1418,669,1569]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 24. Bradabyssa irenaia (Chamberlin, 1919) n. comb., holotype (USNM 19340). A. Dorsal view. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, right lateral view, head exposed, eroded (Br: branchial scars, Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). D. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes; VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). E. Chaetiger 15, right parapodium, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. F. Chaetiger 9, right parapodium, tips of smaller neurospines and medial portion of a larger, broken neurospine (inset: neurospine tip). G. Posterior end, dorsal view. Scale bars: A: 3.2 mm, B: 1.3 mm, C: 0.5 mm, D: 0.8 mm, E: 20 µm, F: 100 µm, G: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041258/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig. 24A</figureCitation>
); 43(27+16) mm long, 
<quantity box="[760,852,1789,1814]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
wide, cephalic cage chaetae broken, 41 (23+18) chaetigers. Tunic papillated, dorsal papillae larger, globular, in 4–5 alternating series per chaetiger (
<figureCitation box="[1317,1423,1825,1850]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1613,1635]" captionTargetBox="[175,1416,673,1567]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[171,1418,669,1569]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 24. Bradabyssa irenaia (Chamberlin, 1919) n. comb., holotype (USNM 19340). A. Dorsal view. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, right lateral view, head exposed, eroded (Br: branchial scars, Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). D. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes; VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). E. Chaetiger 15, right parapodium, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. F. Chaetiger 9, right parapodium, tips of smaller neurospines and medial portion of a larger, broken neurospine (inset: neurospine tip). G. Posterior end, dorsal view. Scale bars: A: 3.2 mm, B: 1.3 mm, C: 0.5 mm, D: 0.8 mm, E: 20 µm, F: 100 µm, G: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041258/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig. 24B</figureCitation>
), ventral papillae smaller, arranged in 8–9 alternating series per chaetiger, each with smaller or larger papillae; without thick tunic, sediment grains adherent to papillae, not forming large tubercles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,1681,2030]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
Anterior end exposed, mostly eroded (
<figureCitation box="[670,824,1933,1958]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1613,1635]" captionTargetBox="[175,1416,673,1567]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[171,1418,669,1569]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 24. Bradabyssa irenaia (Chamberlin, 1919) n. comb., holotype (USNM 19340). A. Dorsal view. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, right lateral view, head exposed, eroded (Br: branchial scars, Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). D. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes; VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). E. Chaetiger 15, right parapodium, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. F. Chaetiger 9, right parapodium, tips of smaller neurospines and medial portion of a larger, broken neurospine (inset: neurospine tip). G. Posterior end, dorsal view. Scale bars: A: 3.2 mm, B: 1.3 mm, C: 0.5 mm, D: 0.8 mm, E: 20 µm, F: 100 µm, G: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041258/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig. 24C, D</figureCitation>
). Prostomium eroded. Caruncle eroded posteriorly, separating branchial plate, median keel and lateral ridges eroded, probably converging posteriorly. Palps large, one missing, remaining one with tip partially eroded, not corrugated; palp keels low, rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,151,614]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Branchiae missing, branchial scars arranged into two lateral groups, each with filaments in radiating series, about 110 scars per group. Individual lips not discernable, smashed and eroded (ventral pharyngeal bulb slightly exposed). Nephridial lobe scars in lower half of branchial plate, each as rounded darker lobes.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,151,614]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Cephalic cage probably present (notochaetae in chaetiger 4 very long), chaetae as long as 1/8 body length, or slightly shorter than body width. Chaetal lobes of chaetiger 1 with chaetal bases arranged in short lateral series, chaetal number unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,151,614]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
Anterior dorsal margin of first chaetiger rounded, papillated. Anterior chaetigers with anteroventral filaments, probably epizoans. Chaetigers 1–3 of similar length. Chaetal transition from cephalic cage to body chaetae abrupt; aristate neurospines present from chaetiger 2 (most broken, bases remain). Gonopodial lobes dark, rounded, short lobes in chaetiger 5 (
<figureCitation box="[385,490,481,506]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1613,1635]" captionTargetBox="[175,1416,673,1567]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[171,1418,669,1569]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 24. Bradabyssa irenaia (Chamberlin, 1919) n. comb., holotype (USNM 19340). A. Dorsal view. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, right lateral view, head exposed, eroded (Br: branchial scars, Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). D. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes; VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). E. Chaetiger 15, right parapodium, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. F. Chaetiger 9, right parapodium, tips of smaller neurospines and medial portion of a larger, broken neurospine (inset: neurospine tip). G. Posterior end, dorsal view. Scale bars: A: 3.2 mm, B: 1.3 mm, C: 0.5 mm, D: 0.8 mm, E: 20 µm, F: 100 µm, G: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041258/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 24D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,151,614]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Parapodia well developed, lateral. Notopodia and neuropodia close to each other. Median neuropodia ventrolateral. Notopodia short low rounded lobes, with 3–4 long papillae. Neuropodia larger rounded lobe, 8–10 marginal papillae (mostly eroded), each with globular base.</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041258/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" targetBox="[175,1416,673,1567]" targetPageId="48">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1436,1613,1789]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,290,1613,1635]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">FIGURE 24.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Chamberlin, 1919)" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[298,708,1613,1635]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="irenaia" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[298,498,1613,1635]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Bradabyssa irenaia</emphasis>
(Chamberlin, 1919)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[717,810,1613,1635]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, holotype (USNM 19340). A. Dorsal view. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, right lateral view, head exposed, eroded (Br: branchial scars, Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). D. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes; VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). E. Chaetiger 15, right parapodium, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. F. Chaetiger 9, right parapodium, tips of smaller neurospines and medial portion of a larger, broken neurospine (inset: neurospine tip). G. Posterior end, dorsal view. Scale bars: A: 3.2 mm, B: 1.3 mm, C: 0.5 mm, D: 0.8 mm, E: 20 µm, F: 100 µm, G: 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1436,1828,2002]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
Median notochaetae arranged in short transverse series; all notochaetae multiarticulate capillaries, articles short basally and medially, distally long (
<figureCitation box="[646,754,1867,1892]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1613,1635]" captionTargetBox="[175,1416,673,1567]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[171,1418,669,1569]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 24. Bradabyssa irenaia (Chamberlin, 1919) n. comb., holotype (USNM 19340). A. Dorsal view. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, right lateral view, head exposed, eroded (Br: branchial scars, Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). D. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes; VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). E. Chaetiger 15, right parapodium, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. F. Chaetiger 9, right parapodium, tips of smaller neurospines and medial portion of a larger, broken neurospine (inset: neurospine tip). G. Posterior end, dorsal view. Scale bars: A: 3.2 mm, B: 1.3 mm, C: 0.5 mm, D: 0.8 mm, E: 20 µm, F: 100 µm, G: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041258/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 24E</figureCitation>
); 6–8 per bundle, as long as 1/3 body width. Chaetiger 1 neurochaetae missing, aristate neurospines from chaetiger 2, most eroded, few smaller ones with tips aristate, tapered, slightly curved (
<figureCitation box="[441,544,1941,1966]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1613,1635]" captionTargetBox="[175,1416,673,1567]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[171,1418,669,1569]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 24. Bradabyssa irenaia (Chamberlin, 1919) n. comb., holotype (USNM 19340). A. Dorsal view. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, right lateral view, head exposed, eroded (Br: branchial scars, Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). D. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes; VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). E. Chaetiger 15, right parapodium, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. F. Chaetiger 9, right parapodium, tips of smaller neurospines and medial portion of a larger, broken neurospine (inset: neurospine tip). G. Posterior end, dorsal view. Scale bars: A: 3.2 mm, B: 1.3 mm, C: 0.5 mm, D: 0.8 mm, E: 20 µm, F: 100 µm, G: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041258/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 24F</figureCitation>
); 7–8 per bundle, arranged in È-shaped patterns; each neurospine with rings short, decreasing in length medially and distally, penetrating aristal basis, tip hyaline, recurved.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1437,151,824]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
Posterior end tapered into rounded lobe (
<figureCitation box="[666,773,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1613,1635]" captionTargetBox="[175,1416,673,1567]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[171,1418,669,1569]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 24. Bradabyssa irenaia (Chamberlin, 1919) n. comb., holotype (USNM 19340). A. Dorsal view. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, right lateral view, head exposed, eroded (Br: branchial scars, Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). D. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes; VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). E. Chaetiger 15, right parapodium, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. F. Chaetiger 9, right parapodium, tips of smaller neurospines and medial portion of a larger, broken neurospine (inset: neurospine tip). G. Posterior end, dorsal view. Scale bars: A: 3.2 mm, B: 1.3 mm, C: 0.5 mm, D: 0.8 mm, E: 20 µm, F: 100 µm, G: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041258/files/figure.png" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Fig. 24G</figureCitation>
); pygidium with anus dorso-terminal, round opening; anal cirri absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="49" pageNumber="50" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1437,151,824]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,223,248]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Chamberlin, 1919)" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[323,774,223,248]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="irenaia" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[323,543,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Bradabyssa irenaia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Chamberlin" box="[559,765,223,248]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" refString="Chamberlin, R. V. (1919) The Annelida Polychaeta of the Albatross Tropical Pacific Expedition, 1891 - 1905. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard College, 48, 1 - 514. Available from: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 25672  page / 7 / mode / 1 up &amp; plates: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 21704  page / 7 / mode / 1 up (Accessed 2 Oct. 2017)" type="journal article" year="1919">Chamberlin, 1919</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[782,881,223,248]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Chamberlin, 1919)" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[1032,1407,223,248]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="verrucosa" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[1032,1176,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. verrucosa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Chamberlin" box="[1192,1398,223,248]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" refString="Chamberlin, R. V. (1919) The Annelida Polychaeta of the Albatross Tropical Pacific Expedition, 1891 - 1905. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard College, 48, 1 - 514. Available from: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 25672  page / 7 / mode / 1 up &amp; plates: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 21704  page / 7 / mode / 1 up (Accessed 2 Oct. 2017)" type="journal article" year="1919">Chamberlin, 1919</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="49" pageNumber="50">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, both coming from abyssal sediments in the 
<collectingRegion box="[721,805,261,284]" country="Sri Lanka" name="Eastern" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Eastern</collectingRegion>
Pacific, by the relative size of the larger dorsal papillae. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,299,296,320]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="irenaia">
In 
<emphasis box="[184,299,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. irenaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there is no large epi-notopodial papillae, whereas there is one in 
<emphasis box="[1066,1218,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[1066,1214,297,320]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="verrucosa">B. verrucosa</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
another difference being that there are 8–9 ventral transverse series of papillae 
<taxonomicName box="[868,1016,332,357]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="irenaia">
in 
<emphasis box="[901,1016,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. irenaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
whereas there are only 2–3 ventral transverse series in the latter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1437,151,824]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
<bibRefCitation author="Chamberlin" box="[199,466,404,429]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" refString="Chamberlin, R. V. (1919) The Annelida Polychaeta of the Albatross Tropical Pacific Expedition, 1891 - 1905. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard College, 48, 1 - 514. Available from: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 25672  page / 7 / mode / 1 up &amp; plates: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 21704  page / 7 / mode / 1 up (Accessed 2 Oct. 2017)" type="journal article" year="1919">Chamberlin (1919:401)</bibRefCitation>
regarded 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[585,700,405,428]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="irenaia">
<emphasis box="[585,700,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. irenaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as closely resembling 
<taxonomicName authority="(Rathke, 1843)" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Rathke" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[970,1263,404,429]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Brada" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[970,1079,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. villosa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rathke" box="[1097,1255,404,429]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" refString="Rathke, H. (1843) Beitrage zur Fauna Norwegens. Verhandlungen der Kaiserlichen Leopoldinisch-Carolinischen Akademie der Naturforscher, 20, 1 - 264. Available from: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 43961  page / 7 / mode / 1 up (Accessed 2 Oct. 2017)" type="journal article" year="1843">Rathke, 1843</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, and separated them by the relative chaetal size. The 
<typeStatus box="[576,624,440,464]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">type</typeStatus>
and number of papillae provide more striking differences; most papillae in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Rathke" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[184,295,476,501]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Brada" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[184,295,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are of similar size and slightly swollen basally, whereas 
<taxonomicName box="[974,1123,476,501]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="irenaia">
in 
<emphasis box="[1007,1123,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. irenaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
dorsal papillae are of two markedly different sizes. 
<taxonomicName box="[457,652,511,536]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="irenaia">
Thus, 
<emphasis box="[534,652,513,536]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. irenaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles those species that possess dorsal papillae arranged in alternating size and position, but it differs from these by the number of transverse series of papillae, as stated in the key above.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1437,151,824]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
However, as indicated above, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Chamberlin, 1919)" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[547,1002,620,645]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="irenaia" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[547,769,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Bradabyssa irenaia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Chamberlin" box="[786,994,620,645]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" refString="Chamberlin, R. V. (1919) The Annelida Polychaeta of the Albatross Tropical Pacific Expedition, 1891 - 1905. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard College, 48, 1 - 514. Available from: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 25672  page / 7 / mode / 1 up &amp; plates: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 21704  page / 7 / mode / 1 up (Accessed 2 Oct. 2017)" type="journal article" year="1919">Chamberlin, 1919</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1012,1113,620,645]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
also resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fauchald, 1972)" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Fauchald" baseAuthorityYear="1972" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abyssalis" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[1299,1436,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. abyssalis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Fauchald" box="[158,341,655,680]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" refString="Fauchald, K. (1972) Benthic polychaetous annelids from deep waters off Western Mexico and adjacent areas in the Eastern Pacific Ocean. Allan Hancock Monographs in Marine Biology, 7, 1 - 575." type="journal article" year="1972">Fauchald, 1972</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[363,467,655,680]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
by having about 5 series of dorsal tubercles. They differ because 
<taxonomicName box="[1283,1436,655,680]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="irenaia">
in 
<emphasis box="[1318,1436,657,680]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. irenaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
neurochaetae are tapered and integument is dark, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Fauchald" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[872,1010,692,717]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abyssalis">
<emphasis box="[872,1010,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. abyssalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
neurochaetae are medially cleft and integument is pale. Furthermore, 
<taxonomicName box="[535,680,727,752]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="irenaia">
in 
<emphasis box="[566,680,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. irenaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
notochaetae have short rings basally and medially, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Fauchald" baseAuthorityYear="1972" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abyssalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B. abyssalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are present only basally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1187,799,824]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1437,151,824]" box="[199,1187,799,824]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,799,824]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Distribution</emphasis>
. Pacific Ocean, off 
<collectingCountry box="[568,660,800,823]" name="Panama" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
<collectingRegion box="[568,660,800,823]" country="Panama" name="Panama" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Panama</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
, in sediments deeper than 
<quantity box="[956,1041,800,824]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" unit="m" value="3200.0">3200 m</quantity>
water depth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
